{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1e5dec5b-e955-4494-9bf3-b627d467b285","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n**1. Get a shell into the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present):**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**3. Find your app's PID:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**4. Collect the trace:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can copy out and analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n**To copy the trace off the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Alternative — if `dotnet-trace` can't be installed** (e.g., no SDK/internet):\n- Use **PerfView** or **dotnet-monitor** as a sidecar.\n- Or enable [EventPipe via environment variables](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/eventpipe) before the process starts:\n  ```\n  DOTNET_EnableEventPipe=1\n  DOTNET_EventPipeOutputPath=C:\\trace.nettrace\n  ```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"128e4c77-0699-436c-b415-b4727b4c22d7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":429},"id":"ae13c383-e523-4166-9fae-e8f4710aefe2","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:46:19.773Z","parentId":"6f3a72d6-88e8-4965-95df-98044b3dc416"}
